SIMPLE: ics
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -ics
<hw>-ics</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <def>A suffix used in forming the names of
certain sciences, systems, etc., as acoust<xex>ics</xex>,
mathemat<xex>ics</xex>, dynam<xex>ics</xex>, statist<xex>ics</xex>,
polit<xex>ics</xex>, athlet<xex>ics</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ The names sciences ending in <xex>ics</xex>, as
<xex>mathematics</xex>, <xex>mechanics</xex>, <xex>metaphysics</xex>,
<xex>optics</xex>, etc., are, with respect to their form, nouns in the
plural number. The plural form was probably introduced to mark the
complex nature of such sciences; and it may have been in imitation of
the use of the Greek plurals <?/, <?/, <?/, <?/, etc., to designate
parts of Aristotle's writings. Previously to the present century, nouns
ending in <xex>ics</xex> were construed with a verb or a pronoun in the
plural; but it is now generally considered preferable to treat them as
singular. In Greman we have <xex>die Mathematik</xex>, <xex>die
Mechanik</xex>, etc., and in French <xex>la metaphysique</xex>, <xex>la
optique</xex>, etc., corresponding to our <xex>mathematics</xex>,
<xex>mechanics</xex>, <xex>metaphysics</xex>, <xex>optics</xex>,
etc.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mathematics have</qex> for their object the consideration of
whatever is capable of being numbered or measured.</q> <rj><qau>John
Davidson.</qau></rj></p>

<p>The citations subjoined will serve as examples of the best present
usage.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ethics is the sciences of the laws which govern our actions as
moral agents.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All parts of knowledge have their origin in
<qex>metaphysics</qex>, and finally, perhaps, revolve into
<qex>it</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mechanics</qex>, like pure <qex>mathematics</qex>, may be
geometrical, or may be analytical; that is, <it>it</it> may treat space
either by a direct consideration of its properties, or by a symbolical
representation.</q> <rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><-- p. 725 --></p>

<p><ent>Icteric</ent>⟦br⟧
